*** version 075, Apr 12, change log: 
Added Code for switching dynamically between multiple classes of characters in the game,
 while having only one character active at one time.
 You need to add and patch your existing 2 player game. 
 Basically, a list of jumper classes and an index thorough that list, allows to cycle through it, even during game play.
 So you can switch between an arbitrary number of characters with various powers during the game play 
 (e.g, one class could be good at jumping, so great at collecting prizes,
 while another jumper class may have the ability to shoot, so good to use in a boss fight!).

*** version 07, Apr 11, 2021 change log: 
Foam Bullets and shooting:
  - a bullet object is like a hurdle but moving in the opposite direction and starting from the jumper current position
  - can destroy hurdles when colliding with them - so collision behaviour is similar to hurdle killing the jumper
  Steps:
    1) make a copy of the hurdle.py and name it bullet.py
    2) rename all references to Hurdle class in bullet.py to Bullet
    3) find a suitable sprite map for the Bullets and modify the __init__() to load them up
    4) create a new constant BULLET_VELOCITY, set it to a suitable value (30 seems ok) and use it instead of HURDLE_VELOCITY
    5a) modify the physics of the bullet in the move() method so that the X position increase with the velocity value
          self.posX += self.velocityX + MOVE_TIME_CONST * self.accelX
    5b) also, when the bullet reaches the right side of the screen, it should not wrap around like hurdles do, but disappear so:
        if self.posX > HGame.Width:
          HGame.HideSprite(self) #object removes itself from all sprite group
    5c) also, the bullet will never reach the left side of the screen so this code is non-functional and can be removed:
        if self.posX < -self.rect.width // 2:
          self.mutate()
          self.posX = HGame.Width
    
    6) the bullets do not mutate or reset, rather they fly so, we need to merge the mutate() and reset() methods into fly(self,posX,posY);
    this way the posX and posY parameters where the bullet starts flying can be passed along to reflect the jumper position
    remove the calls to mutate() and reset() in the __init__() as well
    6a) since the Y position is not random anymore (like the hurdles) in the new fly() method add the bullet object to the all sprites group 
    so that it becomes visible, set the start X and Y position, the X velocity and create a boolean flag that indicates the bullet is flying
        HGame.ShowSprite(self)
        self.rect.midbottom = (HGame.Width,posY)
        self.posX=posX
        self.velocityX=BULLET_VELOCITY
        self.accelX=0
        self.flying=True
    7) when the bullet object is created, i.e., in the __ini__() method set the flying boolean to false:
        self.flying=False
    
  But where is the bullet object created, updated, etc.? clearly, bullets are attached to the jumper that can shoot them! So:
    8) add a bullet object to the jumper object by initializing one in the __init__() of the jumper:
      self.bullet=Bullet()
    8a) clearly for this to work, you need to import the Bullet class in jumper.py:
      from bullet import Bullet
    9) in the main game update() method, we must call bullet.move() if the bullet is flying:
      if jumper.bullet.flying:
        jumper.bullet.move()
    10) to trigger shooting, clearly a new key event needs to be handled: 
      ...
      elif e.key == pygame.K_DELETE:
          jumper.bullet.fly(jumper.posX,jumper.posY)
  At this point, if all is right, your jumper should shoot colorful sanitizer foam bubble bullets! But they are useless and no sound (:
  We'll fix that by:
    11) adding a shoot sound in the Jumper class and playing the sound when the shooting key is pressed; this is easy;
      NOTE: the sound object could also be added to the bullet class (this is probably even more appropriate)
    12) making the collisions between bullet and hurdles work; clearly this happens in the update() method of the game where,
    when a bullet is flying, right after the jumper.bullet.move() call, we should check for collisions with the hurdle:
      jumper.bullet.check_collisions_with(hurdle)
    13) if all is well, the game will crash when the foam bullet hits a virus because the virus does not have a self.dead property and a 
    die() method implemented;
    you need to fix that!
      def die(self):
        #needs dramatic explosion here, but for now, just call mutate() and reset()
        self.mutate()
        self.reset()

Clearly now, with the new shooting powers of the main character, the game has become too easy so additional tweaks are needed!
So try to experiment more!

still lots left to do!
*** version 065, March 29, change log: 
- added countdown timer at the beginning of game
- moved game timers code in separate files
- made the boolean flags that drive game logic properties of the HGame object, 
  for easy access and improved code readability (no more global defs and annoying bugs)


*** version 06, March 27, change log: 
- major refactoring of code base
- added Timer class to simplify the use of timers
- added game Pause (BLANK key) functionality
- implemented two phases game state logic - Game Ready / Game On
    - Game ready - moveable jumper, hurdle or prize collisions disabled
    - Game on - hurdle or prize collisions enabled
- added timer for the game ending dramatic sequence
- moved jumper sprite dictionary/database into consts.py
- moved the platform class outside the main game code, into floor.py
- added sprites to the hurdles (ugly coronavirus variants) and randomness to the hurdles vertical position


*** version 05, March 24, change log: 
- added new class SpriteMap to make loading sprites from spritesheets more flexible
- modified the jumper __init__() code to accomodate the new way of loading sprites
- creating a second player is a bit more complicated now when spritesheets are not identical
  the easiest is to create another class Jumper2 and duplicate the code from original Jumper,
  and modify the bits that differ between the two players (e.g., sprites, behaviour, physics, etc.)
- modified the collectibles to add a new type of Prize: an elusive (5% probability to appear) COVID19 vaccine shot


*** version 04, March 16, change log: 
- added coin count and display
- refactored collectibles.py
- added collision immunity property for jumper - not triggered by anything yet (coin count?)


*** version 03, March 10, change log: 
- split codebase into separate files
- added collectibles, prizes, coins so that player has an objective other than not dying
- more sound effects and additional sprites (bitcoins)
- refactored classes, methods names and identifiers for clarity
- added more comments
- renamed the game entry point game.py from hurdler_game.py


*** version 02, March 09, change log: 
  - cleaned up codebase, moved around some code
  - removed less hard-coded file paths
  - added additional properties and methods to the game module, to make it easier to change background image and music
  - updated README file to collect links to image and sound assets borrowed from the internet (have to watch for license terms)

*** version 01, Jan 2020
- first version, mostly based on existing learning resources
- at least the sprites and sounds work well!


